  "tasks": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "priority": 1,
      "title": "Verify network connectivity to critical endpoints",
      "description": "Execute ping tests to key internal and external hosts to confirm reachability and latency.",
      "status": "failed",
      "type": "command"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "priority": 2,
      "title": "Check system interface status and configuration",
      "description": "Use system tools to inspect active network interfaces, IP addresses, and routing tables for anomalies.",
      "status": "done",
      "type": "read"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "priority": 3,
      "title": "Assess network performance metrics",
      "description": "Analyze packet loss, jitter, and bandwidth utilization using diagnostic CLI tools.",
      "status": "failed",
      "type": "analysis"
    }
  ],
  "plans": [
    {
      "plan_step_id": 1,
      "task_id": 1,
      "step_index": 0,
      "type": "analysis",
      "solution": {
        "approach": "Identify the list of critical internal and external endpoints that need connectivity verification. Determine which hosts are considered critical based on operational requirements, such as internal services (e.g., database servers, application servers) and external dependencies (e.g., API gateways, DNS resolvers). This step ensures all target hosts are known before proceeding with tests."
      },
      "dependencies": [],
      "status": "failed"
    },
    {
      "plan_step_id": 2,
      "task_id": 1,
      "step_index": 1,
      "type": "design",
      "solution": {
        "approach": "Design a sequence of ping commands for each identified endpoint using the `ping` CLI tool with appropriate parameters: use `-c 4` to send exactly four ICMP packets per host, and `-W 3` to set a 3-second timeout per packet. This balances diagnostic depth with performance. No output redirection or file logging is used; results will be captured via stdout capture in subsequent steps."
      },
      "dependencies": [
        1
      ],
      "status": "pending"
    },
    {
      "plan_step_id": 3,
      "task_id": 1,
      "step_index": 2,
      "type": "implementation",
      "solution": {
        "approach": "Execute individual `ping` commands for each critical endpoint using `run_shell_command`. For example: `ping -c 4 -W 3 internal-db.example.com`, followed by external endpoints like `google-public-dns-a.google.com`. Capture stdout directly without redirecting to files. This approach leverages existing system tools for efficiency and avoids unnecessary script creation."
      },
      "dependencies": [
        2
      ],
      "status": "pending"
    },
    {
      "plan_step_id": 4,
      "task_id": 1,
      "step_index": 3,
      "type": "validation",
      "solution": {
        "approach": "Analyze the output of each `ping` command to determine reachability and latency metrics. Validate that each endpoint responded within the timeout window and compute average round-trip time if successful. Flag any host with no responses or excessive latency as unreachable or degraded. Use direct stdout inspection—no parsing scripts unless absolutely necessary."
      },
      "dependencies": [
        3
      ],
      "status": "pending"
    },
    {
      "plan_step_id": 5,
      "task_id": 2,
      "step_index": 0,
      "type": "analysis",
      "solution": {
        "approach": "Begin by identifying active network interfaces using standard CLI tools. Use `ip link show` or `ifconfig` to list all interfaces and determine their operational state (UP/DOWN). This provides a baseline view of interface availability.",
        "algorithm": "Execute shell command: `ip -br -c link show`",
        "complexity": "O(n) where n is the number of network interfaces"
      },
      "dependencies": [],
      "status": "done"
    },
    {
      "plan_step_id": 6,
      "task_id": 2,
      "step_index": 1,
      "type": "analysis",
      "solution": {
        "approach": "Retrieve IP address assignments for each active interface using `ip addr show`. Focus on IPv4 and IPv6 addresses, subnet masks, and any duplicate or unexpected IP configurations that may indicate misconfiguration.",
        "algorithm": "Execute shell command: `ip -br -c addr show`",
        "complexity": "O(m) where m is the number of configured addresses"
      },
      "dependencies": [
        5
      ],
      "status": "done"
    },
    {
      "plan_step_id": 7,
      "task_id": 2,
      "step_index": 2,
      "type": "analysis",
      "solution": {
        "approach": "Inspect the routing table using `ip route show` to identify default gateways, static routes, and potential anomalies such as multiple default routes or unreachable networks.",
        "algorithm": "Execute shell command: `ip -br -c route show`",
        "complexity": "O(r) where r is the number of routing entries"
      },
      "dependencies": [
        5
      ],
      "status": "done"
    },
    {
      "plan_step_id": 8,
      "task_id": 2,
      "step_index": 3,
      "type": "validation",
      "solution": {
        "approach": "Compare current interface states, IP assignments, and routes against known good configurations. Look for interfaces marked UP but without IP assignment, conflicting routes, or missing expected gateway. Flag any deviations from baseline expectations.",
        "algorithm": "Manual inspection and logical comparison; no automated script needed unless custom logic is required.",
        "complexity": "O(1) per anomaly detected"
      },
      "dependencies": [
        5,
        6,
        7
      ],
      "status": "done"
    },
    {
      "plan_step_id": 9,
      "task_id": 3,
      "step_index": 0,
      "type": "analysis",
      "solution": {
        "approach": "Identify available network diagnostic tools on the system to measure packet loss, jitter, and bandwidth utilization. Determine if common CLI tools like ping, mtr, iperf3, or netperf are installed and functional.",
        "algorithm": "Check for presence of ping, mtr, iperf3 via 'which' or 'command -v', then test basic functionality with simple commands like 'ping -c 5 google.com' to assess reachability and baseline latency.",
        "complexity": "O(1) - constant time checks"
      },
      "dependencies": [],
      "status": "done"
    },
    {
      "plan_step_id": 10,
      "task_id": 3,
      "step_index": 1,
      "type": "design",
      "solution": {
        "approach": "Design a sequence of CLI-based measurements: (1) Use 'mtr' to assess packet loss and jitter over a sustained period; (2) Use 'iperf3' in client mode to measure bandwidth utilization against a known server; (3) Parse output directly without file redirection to avoid absolute paths and temporary files.",
        "algorithm": "Sequential execution: First run mtr with count and interval options, then initiate iperf3 client connection. All outputs captured via stdout redirection into variables or immediate processing.",
        "complexity": "O(n) where n is number of packets or duration of test"
      },
      "dependencies": [],
      "status": "failed"
    },
    {
      "plan_step_id": 11,
      "task_id": 3,
      "step_index": 2,
      "type": "implementation",
      "solution": {
        "approach": "Execute the designed diagnostics: Run 'mtr --report-wide --report-cycles=100 <target>' to collect packet loss and jitter data, then run 'iperf3 -c <server> -t 30' to measure bandwidth. Capture both outputs directly using command substitution or shell piping to avoid file I/O.",
        "algorithm": "Use run_shell_command for each tool invocation, specifying target host and parameters. Assume default gateway or public IP as fallback target if none provided.",
        "complexity": "I/O bound, dependent on network stability"
      },
      "dependencies": [
        9,
        10
      ],
      "status": "pending"
    },
    {
      "plan_step_id": 12,
      "task_id": 3,
      "step_index": 3,
      "type": "validation",
      "solution": {
        "approach": "Validate that all three metrics—packet loss (< 1%), jitter (< 30ms), and bandwidth (> 90% of expected)—are within acceptable thresholds. Extract key values from raw CLI output using grep/sed/awk patterns and compare against baselines.",
        "algorithm": "Parse mtr summary for %loss and avg/jitter stats; parse iperf3 output for transfer rate and retransmits. Flag anomalies if conditions fail.",
        "complexity": "O(m) where m is line count of output"
      },
      "dependencies": [
        11
      ],
      "status": "pending"
    }
